import pandas as pd

# 1. Load the "dirty" dataset
df = pd.read_csv('raw_data.csv')

# 2. Remove exact duplicates
df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

# 3. Handle missing values
# Fill numeric missing values with the average
df['Salary'] = df['Salary'].fillna(df['Salary'].mean())
# Drop rows where critical info (like 'User_ID') is missing
df.dropna(subset=['User_ID'], inplace=True)

# 4. Standardize Text (Case & Whitespace)
df['City'] = df['City'].str.strip().str.title()

# 5. Result
print("Cleaned Dataset Info:")
print(df.info())

Statistical Accuracy: If you have 10 duplicate rows of a high-salary employee, your "average salary" calculation will be artificially inflated and incorrect.
Algorithm Stability: Most Machine Learning models will literally crash or throw errors if they encounter a NaN (Not a Number) value during training.
Searchability: If your data has "apple" and "Apple ", a computer sees them as two different fruits. Standardizing text ensures your filters and "Group By" operations work perfectly.
Professional Credibility: Insights derived from "dirty" data lead to bad business decisions. A "Data Doctor" ensures the foundation of the analysis is trustworthy.
